00:49:15.540 --> 00:49:19.890
talking about lived experience
in this kind of complex way.

00:49:19.890 --> 00:49:24.000
But if they're in enough
trouble, they tend to listen.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:27.810
So a healthy crisis
is always a good sign.

00:49:27.810 --> 00:49:31.000
And you can say that the LEGO
company had, at that point

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:34.780
that we're talking about here,
lost around $300,000 a day

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:36.040
for 10 years.

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:39.225
That makes people start
listening a little bit.

00:49:39.225 --> 00:49:44.780
And it's a private company so
it's-- they were in trouble,

00:49:44.780 --> 00:49:46.270
so that tends to help.

00:49:46.270 --> 00:49:46.670
MIKKEL RASMUSSEN:
I also think we've

00:49:46.670 --> 00:49:49.280
experienced, when we talk
especially to people pretty

00:49:49.280 --> 00:49:51.810
high up, that there's a kind
of fatigue with the tools

00:49:51.810 --> 00:49:52.900
they have available.

00:49:52.900 --> 00:49:55.605
There's a fatigue with
the way strategy is done,

00:49:55.605 --> 00:49:57.680
the over-quantification
of everything,

00:49:57.680 --> 00:50:01.170
the million PowerPoint show,
how all the strategies end up

00:50:01.170 --> 00:50:04.640
with the same idea that
we need to fight our core,

00:50:04.640 --> 00:50:06.390
we need to go into
new areas, and we

00:50:06.390 --> 00:50:07.619
need to build capabilities.

00:50:07.619 --> 00:50:08.910
It's always those three things.

00:50:08.910 --> 00:50:11.326
It doesn't matter whether it's
soap or [? tennis cases ?].

00:50:11.326 --> 00:50:12.840
It's the same strategy.

00:50:12.840 --> 00:50:15.660
And we can sense
that there's time

00:50:15.660 --> 00:50:21.070
where those discussions-- and I
think many leaders are looking

00:50:21.070 --> 00:50:23.480
for something new, something
that is deeper and more

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:25.340
inspirational,
basically, I think.

00:50:25.340 --> 00:50:26.881
CHRISTIAN MADSBJERG:
And I would say,

00:50:26.881 --> 00:50:30.110
I'm surprised by how complex
thinkers some of these leaders

00:50:30.110 --> 00:50:31.890
are, actually.

00:50:31.890 --> 00:50:33.180
Which is a nice thing.

00:50:33.180 --> 00:50:36.274
That if you are at
that level, there's

00:50:36.274 --> 00:50:37.690
a reason why you're
at that level.

00:50:37.690 --> 00:50:42.000
And you have bandwidth enough
to deal with many things

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.290
at the same time.

00:50:44.290 --> 00:50:45.790
So that's very
positive, in a sense.

00:50:45.790 --> 00:50:47.130
Thank you.

00:50:47.130 --> 00:50:47.710
MIKKEL RASMUSSEN:
You have a question.

00:50:47.710 --> 00:50:49.876
AUDIENCE: Yeah, so my
question is around thick data.

00:50:49.876 --> 00:50:55.740
And I think guys describe
qualitatively what

00:50:55.740 --> 00:50:58.120
it was, I guess,
in your own style.

00:50:58.120 --> 00:51:02.250
But before you had
this dichotomy of it's

00:51:02.250 --> 00:51:05.015
not focus groups, it's
not explicit questions,

00:51:05.015 --> 00:51:09.360
it's a little more tacit
or a little more subtle.

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:12.430
And I was wondering
how do you go

00:51:12.430 --> 00:51:14.520
about collecting
that thick data?

00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:15.990
Or what's that process like?

00:51:15.990 --> 00:51:19.280
Because it seems more subtle
and a little more responsive

00:51:19.280 --> 00:51:20.320
to the environment.

00:51:20.320 --> 00:51:24.350
And for example, with the
playing with kids example,

00:51:24.350 --> 00:51:28.420
it wasn't just observing
them or taking notes

00:51:28.420 --> 00:51:31.140
but it was also the process
of actually playing with them

00:51:31.140 --> 00:51:33.880
and maybe putting yourself
in their shoes a little bit.

00:51:33.880 --> 00:51:35.870
So I was wondering if
you have any thoughts

00:51:35.870 --> 00:51:38.340
about that methodology
on a larger scale.

00:51:38.340 --> 00:51:40.700
CHRISTIAN MADSBJERG:
So anthropology

00:51:40.700 --> 00:51:45.610
has developed a tools set called
ethnographic data gathering

00:51:45.610 --> 00:51:48.270
from the 1920s and on.

00:51:48.270 --> 00:51:51.020
And it's basically
largely misunderstood

00:51:51.020 --> 00:51:52.180
in business today.

00:51:52.180 --> 00:51:56.940
Because it means in-house,
in-context interviews.

00:51:56.940 --> 00:51:58.530
So interview is
one thing and what

00:51:58.530 --> 00:52:01.670
we say and so on is important,
but it's also important

00:52:01.670 --> 00:52:02.540
what we do.

00:52:02.540 --> 00:52:04.190
And so what we
normally is say is,

00:52:04.190 --> 00:52:06.630
we're not interested
in people, really.

00:52:06.630 --> 00:52:08.390
We're interested in worlds.

00:52:08.390 --> 00:52:11.490
And a world has people
in it, for sure.

00:52:11.490 --> 00:52:13.590
So let's say the
world of cooking,

00:52:13.590 --> 00:52:17.060
or the world of business,
or the world of Google.

00:52:17.060 --> 00:52:19.250
They're all-- or the art world.

00:52:19.250 --> 00:52:22.385
They all have--
it's not a thing.

00:52:22.385 --> 00:52:23.850
The art world is not a thing.

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:26.780
It consists of galleries
and artists and pencils

00:52:26.780 --> 00:52:30.480
and paper and canvases
and all sorts of things.

00:52:30.480 --> 00:52:33.250
And it has roles in there,
so people that feel they're

00:52:33.250 --> 00:52:34.270
artists.

00:52:34.270 --> 00:52:35.660
And it has identities.

00:52:35.660 --> 00:52:36.900
And it has money.

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:38.500
It has all sorts of things.

00:52:38.500 --> 00:52:41.460
In order to understand
a world, you

00:52:41.460 --> 00:52:43.230
need a hook into that world.

00:52:43.230 --> 00:52:45.370
And the way we do that
is through getting

00:52:45.370 --> 00:52:48.580
people and seeing how
they deal with things

00:52:48.580 --> 00:52:50.720
and how they do the
things that they do.

00:52:50.720 --> 00:52:52.580
So it's not that
they can-- I mean,

00:52:52.580 --> 00:52:54.240
they always lie to themselves.

00:52:54.240 --> 00:52:56.840
We all like to ourselves
all the time about,

00:52:56.840 --> 00:52:59.330
I need to cook for my
children all the time

00:52:59.330 --> 00:53:00.980
and then I can't find
my pots and pans.

00:53:00.980 --> 00:53:02.730
That sort of situation.

00:53:02.730 --> 00:53:06.410
And we just try to cut
through that by saying,

00:53:06.410 --> 00:53:10.380
individuals are less
interesting than worlds,

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:11.640
the worlds of people.

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:13.430
So what we study
is not individuals.

00:53:13.430 --> 00:53:15.340
It's world.

00:53:15.340 --> 00:53:17.152
So in a sense--
Margaret Thatcher

00:53:17.152 --> 00:53:19.110
used to say, there is no
such thing as society,

00:53:19.110 --> 00:53:19.780
only individuals.

00:53:19.780 --> 00:53:20.946
We say the other way around.

00:53:20.946 --> 00:53:24.130
We say there is no such thing
as individuals, only societies.

00:53:24.130 --> 00:53:27.600
You are what you do and
the way you do it, but also

00:53:27.600 --> 00:53:29.210
because of all these
other people that

00:53:29.210 --> 00:53:30.350
deeply influence you.

00:53:30.350 --> 00:53:33.201
And you might feel that you
have rational decisions on what

00:53:33.201 --> 00:53:33.700
you do.

00:53:33.700 --> 00:53:34.852
But you don't.

00:53:34.852 --> 00:53:37.310
You make all sorts of decisions
because of your surrounding

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:40.552
and because the world you're in.

00:53:40.552 --> 00:53:42.690
Heidegger calls it the one.

00:53:42.690 --> 00:53:44.780
One does this and one does that.

00:53:44.780 --> 00:53:46.440
That's most of the time.

00:53:46.440 --> 00:53:48.216
We do things because
that's what one does.

00:53:48.216 --> 00:53:49.340
One gets up in the morning.

00:53:49.340 --> 00:53:51.370
One asks questions
when it's uncomfortable

00:53:51.370 --> 00:53:54.290
that nobody's asked questions--
that sort of situation.

00:53:54.290 --> 00:53:56.300
And that's exactly
what we study.

00:53:56.300 --> 00:54:00.890
We study how people
live in worlds

00:54:00.890 --> 00:54:03.660
and how those worlds interact
with them, in a sense.

00:54:03.660 --> 00:54:07.425
So it's observational, but it's
with a theoretical framework

00:54:07.425 --> 00:54:09.752
behind it, in a sense.

00:54:09.752 --> 00:54:10.460
